# Partition, test and train -----------------------------------------------
set.seed(3)

#split clean data into train and test so I can start training models
#This will create an 80/20 split of randomly selected row numbers with 80% train 20% test
bank.Index<-createDataPartition(y=bankdata$y, 
                                p = .8,list = FALSE,times = 1)

# assign the test and train rows to their own data sets
bankTrain<-bankdata[bank.Index,]
bankTest<-bankdata[-bank.Index,]

#Sanity check to verify data has been split 80/20

##             nr.employed
## loanunknown 0
# we see that housingunknown and loanunknown are the same
# Since the other levels of the variable are unique, 
#we can leave it in for model selection

# create null and full models (intact park code)
model.null = glm(y ~ 1, 
                 data = bankTrain,
                 family = binomial) # null model : no predictor
model.full = m1

# stepwise selection with BIC
step.models.BIC<-step(model.null, scope = list(upper=model.full),
                      direction="both",test="Chisq", trace = F, k=log(nrow(bankTrain)))

# stepwise selection with AIC
step.models.AIC<-step(model.null, scope = list(upper=model.full),
                      direction="both",test="Chisq", trace = F) 


summary(step.models.BIC)   # summary of stepwise selection with BIC

#running the model chosen by BIC criteria
m2 <- glm(y ~ nr.employed + poutcome + contact, 
          data = bankTrain,
          family = binomial)
#running the model chosen by AIC criteria
m3 <- glm(y ~ nr.employed + month + contact + campaign + poutcome + cons.conf.idx + loan + previous, 
          data = bankTrain,
          family = binomial)

#get predictions
# this is testing on TEST DATA, so this is test accuracy

#predict full model
bankTest$PredProb.full <- predict.glm(m1, newdata = bankTest, type = 'response')

#predict BIC model
bankTest$PredProb.BIC <- predict.glm(m2, newdata = bankTest, type = 'response')

#predict AIC model
bankTest$PredProb.AIC <- predict.glm(m3, newdata = bankTest, type = 'response')

# Since these are probabilities, we can convert them to binary simply by an ifelse statement.
# try changing this p cutoff to see what happens to accuracy

# Test accuracy on full model

bankTest$PredChoice.full <- ifelse(bankTest$PredProb.full >= 0.5, "yes", "no")

# Test accuracy on BIC model

bankTest$PredChoice.BIC <- ifelse(bankTest$PredProb.BIC >= 0.5, "yes", "no")

# Test accuracy on AIC model

bankTest$PredChoice.AIC <- ifelse(bankTest$PredProb.AIC >= 0.5, "yes", "no")

# We choose BIC model as a better balance of sensitivity and specificity with the same accuracy
# RF MODEL for comparison
set.seed(3)

#Create cross-validation control for the predictive models
# This will tell it to use crossvalidation with 3 repeats
modelControl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", repeats = 3)

#Random Forest model
RF  <- train(y ~ nr.employed + poutcome + contact, 
             method="rf", trControl=modelControl, ntree = 300, data=bankTrain, verbose=FALSE)

#check the cross-validation accuracy results for the three models
print(RF)
## Random Forest 
## 
## 3296 samples
##    3 predictor
##    2 classes: 'no', 'yes' 
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (10 fold, repeated 3 times) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 2967, 2967, 2966, 2966, 2967, 2966, ... 
## Resampling results across tuning parameters:
##

##   2     0.9036194  0.2852672
##   3     0.9037170  0.3204473
##   4     0.9027054  0.3200629
## 
## Accuracy was used to select the optimal model using the largest value.
## The final value used for the model was mtry = 3.
#Evaluate RF on test data set
pred_RF <- predict(RF, newdata=bankTest, type="raw")

#create confusion matrix while it's still a factor type
table(pred = pred_RF, true = bankTest$y)
##      true
## pred   no yes
##   no  720  73
##   yes  13  17
# Get sensitivity and specificity
sensitivity <- sensitivity(pred_RF, bankTest$y)
specificity <- specificity(pred_RF, bankTest$y)


#get test Accuracy estimate for RF
pred_RF <- as.data.frame(pred_RF)
bankTest <- cbind(bankTest, pred_RF)
accuracy_RF <- sum(pred_RF$pred_RF == bankTest$y)/NROW(bankTest)

#RF results table
attribs <- c("accuracy_RF", "sensitivity", "specificity")
vals <- c(accuracy_RF, sensitivity, specificity)
data.frame(attribs, vals)
